{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>BcsE (bacterial cellulose synthase E) or YhjS, is required for cellulose biosynthesis in Salmonella enteritidis. Its role is this process across multiple bacterial species is implied by the partial phylogenetic profiling algorithm. Members are found in the vicinity of other cellulose biosynthesis genes [[cite:PUB00042856], [cite:PUB00086880]].</p>\n\n<p>BcsE contains the C-terminal GIL domain. The GIL domain, for GGDEF I-site like domain, is a c-di-GMP binding domain on the BcsE proteins of enterobacteria. It is not essential for cellulose synthesis but is critical for maximal cellulose production. Cellulose production in enterobacteria is controlled by a two-tiered c-di-GMP-dependent system involving BcsE and the PilZ domain containing glycosyltransferase BcsA. The RxGD motif of the GIL domain is required for c-di-GMP binding [[cite:PUB00075887], [cite:PUB00100649], [cite:PUB00100650], [cite:PUB00100648]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF10995" "Cellulose biosynthesis protein BcsE"}, "ncbifam" {"TIGR03369" "cellulose biosynthesis protein BcsE"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Cellulose biosynthesis protein BcsE", "short" "BcsE"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 7, "domain_architectures" 3, "proteomes" 182, "taxa" 1540, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 2055, "sets" 0, "proteins" 2050, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 1604}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"gp" {"displayName" "Genome Properties", "description" "Genome properties is an annotation system whereby functional attributes can be assigned to a genome, based on the presence of a defined set of protein signatures within that genome.", "rank" 45, "accessions" [{"accession" "GenProp0658", "url" "https://www.ebi.ac.uk/interpro/genomeproperties/genome-property/